issues.title: Mutated + transitive ES6 exports lose type checking
issues.body:
Mutated and transitive exports lose type checking since we transpile each module in isolation, and transpile mutated exports to getters.

Transitive exports include `export {} from` statements but also `import {name}; export {name};`. Transitive exports need to be mutable if the original is, but since we transpile in isolation (and thus don't have this information) they must always be getters.

Going to be a similar fix to #3077 - we need to scan all ES6 modules before any rewriting to understand what exactly it is we're importing.

issues.body:
I searched + [posted on the mailing list](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/closure-compiler-discuss/qKm-TpZbFdU) -- seems like this might be a legit issue, so posting it here, too.

We noticed after a recent upgrade that:

``` js
if (/** @type {Array|undefined} */ (window['c']) === null) {
  window['d'] = 12
}
```

which had previously (as of v20160619) compiled to:

``` js
null===window["c"]&&(window["d"]=12);
```

was now (as of v20160713 and later) compiling to:

``` js
window["c"]||(window["d"]=12);
```

This no longer discriminates between null and undefined, which was surprising to us. Is that a bug? Or are we maybe using annotations incorrectly?

There's a minimal repro at https://github.com/cldellow/closure-q/blob/master/src/main/java/q/Test.java that shows the precise set of options that we used.

issues.title: ES6 transpilation causes syntax error
issues.body:
With whitespace only compilation, language_in = es6_strict, language_out = es6_strict, this code:

``` js
return value => ({foo: 'bar', baz: value});
```

Is changed to:

``` js
return (value) => {foo: 'bar', baz: value};
```

Adding the parens around the arrow function params is nice, but removing it from the body is not okay. The braces are parsed as a function body with higher priority, it needs to be in parens to be parsed as an object literal, which this code wants to do. Or to be absolutely correct, it may be rewritten as:

``` js
return (value) => { return {foo: 'bar', baz: value} }
```

issues.title: Regression: Type of ActiveXObject no longer known
issues.body:
Closure Compiler no longer knows the type of the `window.ActiveXObject` since v20140625. I guess this has something to do with this change:

> Variables in externs are copied to the "window" object. This means
> that properties can be accessed as "window.foo" even if they're only
> declared in the externs as "var foo;"

I searched the externs files and found two declarations. The first one is in `ie_dom.js`:

```
/** @type {function(new:ActiveXObject, string, string=)} */
Window.prototype.ActiveXObject;
```

The second one is in `es3.js`:

```
/**
 * @param {string} progId
 * @param {string=} opt_location
 * @constructor
 * @see http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/7sw4ddf8.aspx
 */
function ActiveXObject(progId, opt_location) {}
```

I'm not sure which one is the correct one but obviously they override each other since the stuff in `window` is now intertwined with the global stuff. The following code no longer works:

```
control = new ActiveXObject(progId);
```

Results in the error message `Could not determine the type of this expression`. My current workaround is this:

```
control = new /** @type {function(new:Object,string)} */ (ActiveXObject)(progId);
```

issues.body:
I was experimenting with an externs file and type checking.

I create an externs file with an event class with an addListener function. As you might expect, the addListener method takes a callback function as a param.

My goal was to then have a JS file that calls addListener() with a function of the wrong type.

I expected to get an error message, but was not getting one, even when the externs file specified a param of one of my classes and the JS code was passing in a function taking a {string}.

I chased the problem down to the addListener's JS-doc within the externs file.  It was:

```
/**
 * @param {function(!bug.MyClass): void} callback.
 */
AnotherClass.prototype.addListener = function(callback) {};
```

Took me quite a while to notice that the param name in the at-param statement is "callback." (contains a trailing dot) so it does not match the name in the function signature.

Normally, when a param is not mentioned in the at-param list, for example:

```
/**
 * @param {number} param2
 */
ewa.prototype.func1 = function(param) {
  console.log(param);
};

```

issues.body:
DeclareGlobalExternsOnWindow assumes that there's a global window, which is not necessarily true. If you're using custom externs for non-browser environments, then window will not exist, and the compiler will spew all sorts of internal errors.

Some possible ideas:
1) DeclareGlobalExternsOnWindow checks if there's a global window, and does nothing if it doesn't exist.
2) DeclareGlobalExternsOnWindow falls back to other global symbols on other environments ("window", "globals", "this")
3) Add a flag to turn this option off

these ideas aren't necessarily mutually exclusive.
thoughts?
